        <div class="title">Android</div>
        <hr><br>
         
        <div class="content">        
        	<div class="subtitle">Life, Death and Miracles</div>
			Android is a linux-based Operative System born in 2003, based on the concept of stack-software. <br>
			Android target platform is ARM ( there is also an x86 implementation ). <br>
			It was initially developed by Android Inc., founded by Google and later bought in 2005, and <br>
			unveiled in 2007 along with the founding of the Open Handset Alliance ( a consortium of hardware, software and telecomunication, companies ). <br>
			<br>
	        <div class="subtitle">Internal Structure</div>
            <table>
	            <tr>
                    <td width=40%>
                        <img src="../res/imgs/android_architecture.png" 
                             alt="Android Architecture"
                             width=100% >       
                    </td>
                    <td width=60%>
					    <table class="content">
						    <tr>								
								<td>
									<div class="strong"> Linux Kernel </div> 
									Android uses linux kernel. <br>
									It provides basic features : <br>
									<ul class="small">
										<li> Hardware Abstraction Layer </li>
										<li> C/C++ APIs. </li>
										<li> GCC. </li>
										<li> Memory and Processes Menagement ( at low-level ) </li>
									</ul>
								</td>
								<td>
								    <div class="strong"> Android Runtime </div> 
									<div class="center"> 
									    Android RT consist essentially of the Dalvik VM and core
										<div class="lessStrong"> C and Java Libraries </div> 
									</div>
									<ul class="small">
										<li> LibC </li>
										<li> OpenGL ES </li>
										<li> Webkit </li>
										<li> SQLite </li>
										<li> ... </li>
									</ul>									
								</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>	
									<div class="strong"> Dalvik VM </div> 
									The Dalvik Virtual Machine is for sure the core of the entire OS. <br>
									It is comparable to the Scheduler of a "classic" OS. <br>
									We'll talk about this in the next chapter. <br>
								</td>
								<td>	
									<div class="strong"> Application Framework </div> 
									This is an other important part of Android. <br>
									It contains most of the libraries needed to develop application, such as the Window Manager, <br>
									but also the Package Manager, and an interface to the telephone APIs.										
								</td>
							</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
            </table>
        </div>

